Can Gap translate social media buzz and nostalgic marketing into sustained =
merchandise success without dedicated product leadership at the helm? For a=
 company that built its empire on perfectly executed basics, the balance be=
tween spectacle and substance may determine whether this apparent comeback =
becomes a lasting transformation or a fleeting moment of paid cultural rele=
vance. At the end of the day, Gap needs merchandise to sell, and it=E2=80=
=99ll be another 12 to 18 months before we see what the merchandise looks l=
ike without Goble=E2=80=99s direction. Furthermore, Dickson isn=E2=80=99t a=
 merchant at
heart; he=E2=80=99s the
marketing guy. We won=E2=80=99t get the Q4 financial results until March, b=
ut marketing can pivot faster than inventory. In other words, it will take =
a few more quarters to find out whether the Gap=E2=80=99s turnaround is rea=
l=E2=80=94or just a clever marketing mirage.

